      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Dumping Ground</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Thomas Outerbridge letter on Mar 18 article cites Fresh Kills landfill as symbol of flawed approach to product design and materials management</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Dumping Ends at Fresh Kills, Symbol of Throw-Away Era'' (front page, March 18) rightly notes most environmentalists would say ''Fresh Kills was a giant accident.'' Many people who don't consider themselves environmentalists would agree.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Dumping Ends at Fresh Kills, Symbol of Throw-Away Era'' (front page, March 18) rightly notes most environmentalists would say ''Fresh Kills was a giant accident.'' Many people who don't consider themselves environmentalists would agree.</p>
        <p>The implication is that our whole approach to product design and materials management has been a giant accident. But the truly frightening thing is that the 3,000-acre Fresh Kills landfill may, in time, become a modest symbol of such tunnel vision, as we deal with the reality of global warming in the wake of a similar approach to energy production and use.</p>
        <p>THOMAS OUTERBRIDGE  New York, March 19, 2001</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
